04501nam a22007215i 9780801455063DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979576283  a97808014550637 a10.7591/97808014550632doi  a(DE-B1597)478621  a(OCoLC)894227822  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJZ 7aPOL0110102bisacsh  aMK 15002rvk1 aRathbun, Brian C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiplomacy's Value :bCreating Security in 1920s Europe and the Contemporary Middle East /cBrian C. Rathbun. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b4 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. The Value and Values of Diplomacy -- t2. Creating Value: A Psychological Theory of Diplomacy -- t3. Tabling the Issue: Two Franco-British Negotiations -- t4. Setting the Table: German Reassurance, British Brokering, and French Understanding -- t5. Getting to the Table -- t6. Cards on the Table -- t7. Turning the Tables -- t8. Additional Value -- t9. Searching for Stresemann -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is the value of diplomacy? How does it affect the course of foreign affairs independent of the distribution of power and foreign policy interests? Theories of international relations too often implicitly reduce the dynamics and outcomes of diplomacy to structural factors rather than the subtle qualities of negotiation. If diplomacy is an independent effect on the conduct of world politics, it has to add value, and we have to be able to show what that value is. In Diplomacy's Value, Brian C. Rathbun sets forth a comprehensive theory of diplomacy, based on his understanding that political leaders have distinct diplomatic styles—coercive bargaining, reasoned dialogue, and pragmatic statecraft.Drawing on work in the psychology of negotiation, Rathbun explains how diplomatic styles are a function of the psychological attributes of leaders and the party coalitions they represent. The combination of these styles creates a certain spirit of negotiation that facilitates or obstructs agreement. Rathbun applies the argument to relations among France, Germany, and Great Britain during the 1920s as well as Palestinian-Israeli negotiations since the 1990s. His analysis, based on an intensive analysis of primary documents, shows how different diplomatic styles can successfully resolve apparently intractable dilemmas and equally, how they can thwart agreements that were seemingly within reach.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801455063zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455063423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801455063/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK